Preheat your #oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve any large @cauliflower florets{300%grams}, then pop them into a large #mixing bowl{} and season with @salt{for seasoning} and @black pepper{for seasoning}. Add the @mayonnaise{64%grams} and toss to coat.

In another small #bowl{}, combine the @panko breadcrumbs{50%grams}, @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet} and the @olive oil{1%tbsp}(for the crumb).

Add the spiced crumbs to the florets and toss to coat evenly.

Pop the crumbed florets onto a lined #baking tray{} and spread them out in a single layer. Discard any leftover crumbs.

When the #oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Cut the @medium tomato{2} into 1cm chunks.

Pop a large #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting lid) on medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

When hot, add the garlic and @korma curry paste{50%grams}. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @water{240%milliliters}(for the bulgur) and bring to the boil. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%grams}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}.

Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

While everything cooks, pick the @mint{1%bunch}(leaves picked) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Pop the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%grams} into a small bowl with half the chopped mint. Season with @salt{for seasoning} and @black pepper{for seasoning}, then mix together. Set the mint yoghurt aside.

When everything's ready, fluff up the bulgur with a #fork{}. Add the tomatoes, remaining mint and half the @mango chutney{40%grams}. Stir until well combined.

Spoon the bulgur wheat into your #bowls{}, then top with the cauliflower nuggets. Serve with a dollop of mint yoghurt and the remaining mango chutney. Enjoy!